### 2.1. Minuscule Coxeter Matroids and the Strong Exchange Property

Let W be a Weyl group associated to the root system \Phi, P\leq W parabolic, and \mathcal{M}\subseteq W/P. Then \mathcal{M} possesses the *strong exchange property* if for all A,B\in\mathcal{M}, there exists a reflection s\in\Phi such that the mirror defined by s separates A and B, and sA,sB\in\mathcal{M}. Observe that this definition mimics the symmetric exchange property for usual matroids. Any collection of cosets with the strong exchange property is a Coxeter matroid [3, Theorem 6.1.2], but the converse fails [3, 4.2.4]. Finally, the *Bruhat order* is a partial ordering on W which extends to W/P. When the resulting poset is a lattice, then P, is said to be *minuscule* [15]. In that case, P is always maximal. That is, P=P\_{r}\coloneqq\langle s\_{1},\dots\hat{s}\_{r},\dots,s\_{n}\rangle.

###### Remark 2.1.

Minuscule parabolic subgroups may also be defined in terms of fundamental weights coming from representation theory. The quotient \mathbb{G}/\mathbb{P} of a reductive group by a parabolic subgroup is naturally a projective variety. For minuscule representations, the ambient projective space of this variety naturally comes with a basis indexed by the cosets of the Weyl group. This allows one to concretely write equations in explicit coordinates that cut out \mathbb{G}/\mathbb{P} [17].

